content.description:
There are two options to start:

Top Flight start:

there was once a ladder below "

Get off the Cart and Climb

" that "

Get off the Cart and Climb

" and Top Flight used to get past the nearly blank start. The ladder is now gone, but you can climb from the ground if you do a powerful little boulder problem (easier if you are tall) into the hole on "

Get off the Cart and Climb

" and then climb slightly right.

Black Nasty start:

this is the "direct" line on Top Flight. Stickclip the black hanger to the right, boink up to where the holds start, and climb straight up. Traditionally you only boink until your right hand is in a bad diagonal pocket and do a hard move to good holds to start. There was once a stool to access the start holds, but it has unfortunately been destroyed.

After the starting shenanigans, climb up fun 5.11, past a little runout to the roof. Just under the roof,Â  you'll find a good kneebar rest. A crux getting over the roof puts you on big holds to the anchors.

content.description:
The Open is a Grade 3 in Durango! "The Open" is nothing new, just a challenge for those bored with our lovely outdoor gym. Enjoy 18 holes (pitches) during a beautiful day out of golf (climbing). There are 38 pitches listed on here to choose from, choose wisely.

Rules:

1. Lead 18 pitches clean.

2. The ratings do not matter, but you won't get it done without climbing at least a couple .12s.

3. You gotta redpoint the pitch before moving on to the next pitch.
content.protection: Fat bolts with even fatter chain.
content.location: Climb in Country Club Cave and Right Side.

content.description: The crux is reaching out of the mail slit.
content.location: This starts straight out from a living (now dead) tree; the one with a horizontal, thin finger slit.

content.description: Do some easy climbing up a block to the first bolt, then traverse right with juggy hands, move up through an overhang, and finish with some less steep face climbing to the anchor.
content.location: This route starts just to the right of the large tree that marks the beginning of the Back 9.

content.description:
This is one of the easier climbs at the Golf Wall. It is a good, pumpy warmup for the other steep routes.

Start on the right side of a bulge at a tall, old tree leaning out from the base of the cliff. Climb past one bolt to a ledge fifteen feet off the ground. Continue up to underneath the roof, and traverse right less than ten feet. Reach for the jug over the roof, and pull up over (crux). Continue up and left to the two bolt carabiner anchor.
This is a little loose down low but better the higher you go - hey, that rhymed!  Head towards a roof pulling one crux only to have another crux pulling the far left lip of said roof.
content.location:
This route starts left of

Burt and Ernie's

and

Black Nasty

on the same start as

Top Flight

but heads up from the big hole instead of cutting right. Most people stick clip the first bolt and then batman up the rope until climbing is possible for them. You can also do a boulder problem from the ground (height-dependent) to access the hole that bumps the grade to 5.12b or c.

content.description:
Gator Pond starts with some stout slab climbing and then goes up steep jugs, slopers, pockets, and crimps ending fighting over a bulge to the anchors of

Putt Putt (AKA Softball and/or Pebble Beach Left)

.

It's a little bit of a squeeze job, but I really enjoy the climbing on this route.

Poop notes: after the 2nd bolt there is a poop den. I cleaned a lot off; however, it can be totally avoided with choosing holds correctly.
content.protection:
5 bolts (you need 5 quickdraws) to quick clips. This shares anchors with

content.description:
Climb the first 5 bolts of

Tee Off On This!

, then break left under the roof. Clip the high bolt, and pull some cool, bouldery moves to clip the new anchor. This fun, burly finish hearkens the spirit of the late local crusher, Bert Perry.
